 Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Weobley Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Weobley, Herefordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1332–Bef 20 September 1388":"about 1332–before 20 September 1388","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1379–Female":"1379–Deceased","1306–1333":"1306–1333","1304–1363":"1304–1363","Bef 20 September 1388":"before 20 September 1388","1363":"1363","1304":"1304","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","Abt 1332":"about 1332","1333":"1333","1465":"1465","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","1306":"1306","Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, England":"Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Weobley Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Weobley, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bromwich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from West Bromwich (Staffs) or Castle and Little Bromwich (Warwicks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brommage","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]},{"name":"Brumage","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bromage  ."]},{"name":"Bromage","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): habitational name from West Bromwich in Staffordshire, or Castle and Little Bromwich in Warwickshire, named in Old English with <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ (the shrub) + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. Compare   Brumage  ."]},{"name":"Brimage","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Brumage  . This name is comparatively rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bromige","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John de Bromwich Justiciar of Ireland was born about 1332, in Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Ralph de Bromwich, was 28 and his mother, Eleanor de Bohum, was 29. He married Katherine. He died before 20 September 1388."},"et":{"Abt 1332–Bef 20 September 1388":"umbes 1332–enne 20. septembrit 1388","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1379–Female":"1379–Surnud","1306–1333":"1306–1333","1304–1363":"1304–1363","Bef 20 September 1388":"enne 20. septembrit 1388","1363":"1363","1304":"1304","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","Abt 1332":"umbes 1332","1333":"1333","1465":"1465","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","1306":"1306","Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, England":"Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Weobley Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Weobley, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1332–Bef 20 September 1388":"noin 1332–ennen vuotta 20. syyskuuta 1388","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","1365–1420":"1365–1420","1375–1465":"1375–1465","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1379–Female":"1379–Kuollut","1306–1333":"1306–1333","1304–1363":"1304–1363","Bef 20 September 1388":"ennen vuotta 20. syyskuuta 1388","1363":"1363","1304":"1304","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1345":"1345","Abt 1332":"noin 1332","1333":"1333","1465":"1465","1388":"1388","1420":"1420","1365":"1365","1332":"1332","1375":"1375","1306":"1306","Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, England":"Bromsberrow, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Weobley Castle, Herefordshire, England":"Weobley, Herefordshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1332–Bef 20 September 1388":"environ 1332–avant 20 septembre 1388","1332–1388":"1332–1388","1345–1411":"1345–1411","136